I think you can issues some warning for this. My way of doing is printing some warnings then a ufunc tries to access only the magnitude part of the quantity.
I added two lines of ```print()```  in ```__getattr__()``` of ```_Quantity``` class in ```quantity.py```, see below:

```python
def __getattr__(self, item):
    # Attributes starting with `__array_` are common attributes of NumPy ndarray.
    # They are requested by numpy functions.
    if item.startswith('__array_'):
        if isinstance(self._magnitude, ndarray):
            print("Warning: the units are stripped")
            return getattr(self._magnitude, item)
        else:
            # If an `__array_` attributes is requested but the magnitude is not an ndarray,
            # we convert the magnitude to a numpy ndarray.
            print("Warning: the units of this non-ndarray are stripped")
            self._magnitude = _to_magnitude(self._magnitude, force_ndarray=True)
            return getattr(self._magnitude, item)
```

You should then get some warning message printed when an unsupported ufunc is called. You may want to replace them with proper ```Warning``` class if you wish.

