The unsoundness of our recovered CFG is resulted from the following:
- Our implementation is not fully flow sensitive. Consider the following code snippet (where `func` is a function pointer):
```
func = 0xbadf00d;
if (always_return_1())
{
    func = printf;
}
func("Hello, world!\n");
```
In this case, `func` should always point to `printf` in reality. But since our implementation is not fully flow sensitive, depending on the order of analysis, `func` may point to either `0xbadf00d` or `printf`. Obviously one of them is incorrect.
- Some of our assumptions are unsound. For example, we are assuming a call will always return to the next instruction after the call instruction if it ever returns, which is not necessarily true.

